            <div type="edition">
                <!-- transcription goes here -->
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Olibula">Olibula</name></persName>, dulcis anima, 
                    <lb n="2"/>quae <expan><abbr>vixi</abbr><ex>t</ex></expan> annis <num value="9">VIIII</num>. In pac<surplus>a</surplus>e.
                </ab>
           
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>"Olibula, sweet in spirit, who lived for nine years. (She rests) in peace."</p>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>Line 1: <persName><name type="cognomen">Olibula</name></persName>: As we might
                    expect with later Latin, the B has taken the place of a classical V,
                            <persName><name type="cognomen">Oliva</name></persName>. The diminutive
                        <hi rend="italic">-ula</hi>â€“ is common, too.</p> 
                <p>Line 2: <hi rend="italic"
                        >vixi</hi>: The verb is meant to be read as a third person singular.  In the vernacular, the final dental was likely to be dropped.</p>
                <p>Line 2: <hi rend="italic">paca<surplus>e</surplus></hi>: The writing of AE for E at the end of the word is a feature of
                    common Latin. The M is missing from EDB and EDCS because it is not
                    recorded in Wilson. I saw a faintly scratched M at the end of
                    the line. I have chosen to restore it with low certainty, though I
                    believe it was never truly carved.</p>
                <p>The letters are irregular in shape, shallow, and unevenly spaced. The two lines
                    of text seem to wiggle around as they approach the right edge of the stone. The
                    chi-rho at the top of the inscription is quite large (6.1 x 5.7) but shows
                    little signs of shading. The lettering of the text has traces of bright red
                    paint, probably applied in the modern period. The letter heights are
                    surprisingly uniform, between 3 and 3.2 cm. The first line measures 48.2 cm in
                    length, while the line below measure 56.3 cm. The L is particularly hard to read, since
                    the second stroke runs down and to the right. The third stroke
                    of the M joins the fourth stroke about midway. The first N in <hi rend="italic"
                        >annis</hi> is also odd; the second and third strokes do not meet and the
                    third strokes curves up and to the left. The loop of the P closes on the <hi
                        rend="italic">hasta</hi>. No words are broken across lines. Interpuncts are
                    only used to set off the numeral from the rest of the text in the second
                    line.</p>
                            </div>



